Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js backend project.

## Changes Made

### Created:
- `src/app/layout.tsx` - Root layout component with Analytics integration
  - Added the `<Analytics />` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
  - Follows Next.js App Router conventions
  - Placed in the root layout to track all pages and API routes

### Modified:
- `package.json` - Added `@vercel/analytics` dependency (version ^2.0.1)
- `package-lock.json` - Updated lockfile with new dependency

## Implementation Details

I fetched the latest official Vercel Analytics documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart to ensure the most up-to-date installation instructions were followed.

The implementation follows the framework-specific instructions for Next.js App Router:
1. Installed `@vercel/analytics` package using npm
2. Created the root layout file at `src/app/layout.tsx`
3. Imported and added the `<Analytics />` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`

This is a minimal, correct implementation that will enable Vercel Web Analytics for this backend project once deployed to Vercel.

## Notes

- The project is a Next.js backend (API-only) without existing layout files
- Created the root layout following Next.js App Router standards
- The Analytics component is placed at the end of the body tag as recommended
- Build errors related to missing Firebase environment variables are expected in the local build environment and not related to this implementation
- Once deployed to Vercel, analytics will need to be enabled in the project dashboard to start collecting data

## Next Steps

After deployment:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel project dashboard
2. Deploy the changes to production
3. Verify the tracking is active by checking for the analytics request in the browser's Network tab
